# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: brownian-motion
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] This motion pattern typically consists of random fluctuations in a particle's position inside a fluid sub-domain, followed by a relocation to another sub-domain.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Each relocation is followed by more fluctuations within the new closed volume.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] This pattern describes a fluid at thermal equilibrium, defined by a given temperature.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Within such a fluid, there exists no preferential direction of flow (as in transport phenomena).
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] More specifically, the fluid's overall linear and angular momenta remain null over time.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The kinetic energies of the molecular Brownian motions, together with those of molecular rotations and vibrations, sum up to the caloric component of a fluid's internal energy (the equipartition theorem).
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] This motion is named after the Scottish botanist Robert Brown, who first described the phenomenon in 1827, while looking through a microscope at pollen of the plant *Clarkia pulchella* immersed in water.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] In 1900, the French mathematician Louis Bachelier modeled the stochastic process now called Brownian motion in his doctoral thesis, The Theory of Speculation (Théorie de la spéculation), prepared under the supervision of Henri Poincaré.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Then, in 1905, theoretical physicist Albert Einstein published a paper in which he modelled the motion of the pollen particles as being moved by individual water molecules, making one of his first major scientific contributions.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The direction of the force of atomic bombardment is constantly changing, and at different times the particle is hit more on one side than another, leading to the seemingly random nature of the motion.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] This explanation of Brownian motion served as convincing evidence that atoms and molecules exist and was further verified experimentally by Jean Perrin in 1908.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Perrin was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1926 "for his work on the discontinuous structure of matter".
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The many-body interactions that yield the Brownian pattern cannot be solved by a model accounting for every involved molecule.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Consequently, only probabilistic models applied to molecular populations can be employed to describe it.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Two such models of the statistical mechanics, due to Einstein and Smoluchowski, are presented below.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Another, pure probabilistic class of models is the class of the stochastic process models.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] There exist sequences of both simpler and more complicated stochastic processes which converge (in the limit) to Brownian motion (see random walk and Donsker's theorem).
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The Roman philosopher-poet Lucretius' scientific poem *On the Nature of Things* (c.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] 60 BC) has a remarkable description of the motion of dust particles in verses 113–140 from Book II.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The formal scientific discovery of this phenomenon is credited to the botanist Robert Brown in 1827.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Brown was studying plant reproduction when he observed pollen grains of the plant *Clarkia pulchella* in water under a simple microscope.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] These grains contain minute particles on the order of 1/4,000th of an inch (6.4 microns) in size.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] He observed these particles executing a continuous, jittery motion.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] By repeating the experiment with particles of inorganic matter, such as glass and rock dust, he was able to rule out that the motion was life-related, although its physical origin was yet to be explained.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The mathematics of much of stochastic analysis, including the mathematics of Brownian motion, was introduced by Louis Bachelier in 1900 in his PhD thesis "The theory of speculation", in which he presented an innovative probabilistic analysis of the stock and option markets.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] However, this pioneering mathematical work connecting random walks to continuous time was largely unknown until the 1950s.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The instantaneous velocity of the Brownian motion can be defined as *v* = Δ*x*/Δ*t*, when Δ*t* << *τ*, where τ is the momentum relaxation time.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] In this way Einstein was able to determine the size of atoms, and how many atoms there are in a mole, or the molecular weight in grams, of a gas.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] In accordance to Avogadro's law, this volume is the same for all ideal gases, namely 22.414 liters at standard temperature and pressure.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The first part of Einstein's argument was to determine how far a Brownian particle travels in a given time interval.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Classical mechanics is unable to determine this distance because of the enormous number of bombardments a Brownian particle will undergo, roughly of the order of 1014 collisions per second.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The integral in the first term is equal to one by the definition of probability, and the second and other even terms (i.e. first and other odd moments) vanish because of space symmetry.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The first moment is seen to vanish, meaning that the Brownian particle is equally likely to move to the left as it is to move to the right.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The second moment is, however, non-vanishing, being given by $\mathbb {E} {\left[x^{2}\right]}=2Dt.$ This equation expresses the mean squared displacement in terms of the time elapsed and the diffusivity.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] From this expression Einstein argued that the displacement of a Brownian particle is not proportional to the elapsed time, but rather to its square root.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] His argument is based on a conceptual switch from the "ensemble" of Brownian particles to the "single" Brownian particle: we can speak of the relative number of particles at a single instant just as well as of the time it takes a Brownian particle to reach a given point.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The second part of Einstein's theory relates the diffusion constant to physically measurable quantities, such as the mean squared displacement of a particle in a given time interval.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] This result enables the experimental determination of the Avogadro number and therefore the size of molecules.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Einstein analyzed a dynamic equilibrium being established between opposing forces.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The beauty of his argument is that the final result does not depend upon which forces are involved in setting up the dynamic equilibrium.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] In his original treatment, Einstein considered an osmotic pressure experiment, but the same conclusion can be reached in other ways.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Consider, for instance, particles suspended in a viscous fluid in a gravitational field.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Gravity tends to make the particles settle, whereas diffusion acts to homogenize them, driving them into regions of smaller concentration.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Under the action of gravity, a particle acquires a downward speed of *v* = *μmg*, where m is the mass of the particle, g is the acceleration due to gravity, and μ is the particle's mobility in the fluid.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] George Stokes had shown that the mobility for a spherical particle with radius r is $\mu ={\tfrac {1}{6\pi \eta r}}$ , where η is the dynamic viscosity of the fluid.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Dynamic equilibrium is established because the more that particles are pulled down by gravity, the greater the tendency for the particles to migrate to regions of lower concentration.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The flux is given by Fick's law, $J=-D{\frac {d\rho }{dh}},$ where *J* = *ρv*.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] In a state of dynamical equilibrium, this speed must also be equal to *v* = *μmg*.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Both expressions for v are proportional to *mg*, reflecting that the derivation is independent of the type of forces considered.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Similarly, one can derive an equivalent formula for identical charged particles of charge q in a uniform electric field of magnitude E, where *mg* is replaced with the electrostatic force *qE*.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] By measuring the mean squared displacement over a time interval along with the universal gas constant *R*, the temperature T, the viscosity η, and the particle radius r, the Avogadro constant *N*A can be determined.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The type of dynamical equilibrium proposed by Einstein was not new.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] It had been pointed out previously by J.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] An identical expression to Einstein's formula for the diffusion coefficient was also found by Walther Nernst in 1888 in which he expressed the diffusion coefficient as the ratio of the osmotic pressure to the ratio of the frictional force and the velocity to which it gives rise.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The former was equated to the law of van 't Hoff while the latter was given by Stokes's law.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] He writes $k'=p_{o}/k$ for the diffusion coefficient k′, where $p_{o}$ is the osmotic pressure and k is the ratio of the frictional force to the molecular viscosity which he assumes is given by Stokes's formula for the viscosity.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Introducing the ideal gas law per unit volume for the osmotic pressure, the formula becomes identical to that of Einstein's.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The use of Stokes's law in Nernst's case, as well as in Einstein and Smoluchowski, is not strictly applicable since it does not apply to the case where the radius of the sphere is small in comparison with the mean free path.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Confirming Einstein's formula experimentally proved difficult.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Initial attempts by Theodor Svedberg in 1906 and 1907 were critiqued by Einstein and by Perrin as not measuring a quantity directly comparable to the formula.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Victor Henri in 1908 took cinematographic shots through a microscope and found quantitative disagreement with the formula but again the analysis was uncertain.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Einstein's predictions were finally confirmed in a series of experiments carried out by Chaudesaigues in 1908 and Perrin in 1909.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The confirmation of Einstein's theory constituted empirical progress for the kinetic theory of heat.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] In essence, Einstein showed that the motion can be predicted directly from the kinetic model of thermal equilibrium.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The importance of the theory lay in the fact that it confirmed the kinetic theory's account of the second law of thermodynamics as being an essentially statistical law.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Smoluchowski's theory of Brownian motion, later contextualized in comprehensive reviews of stochastic physics, starts from the same premise as that of Einstein and derives the same probability distribution *ρ*(*x*, *t*) for the displacement of a Brownian particle along the x axis in time t.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] He therefore gets the same expression for the mean squared displacement: ${\textstyle \mathbb {E} {\left[(\Delta x)^{2}\right]}}$ .
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Associating the kinetic energy ${\textstyle mu^{2}/2}$ with the thermal energy ${\textstyle RT/N}$ , the expression for the mean squared displacement is 64/27 times that found by Einstein.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Smoluchowski attempts to answer the question of why a Brownian particle should be displaced by bombardments of smaller particles when the probabilities for striking it in the forward and rear directions are exactly equal.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] $\mathbb {E} {\left[2m-n\right]}\approx {\sqrt {\frac {n}{2\pi }}}$ showing that the net displacement increases proportionally to the square root of the total population of collision events.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Suppose that a Brownian particle of mass M is surrounded by lighter particles of mass m which are traveling at a speed u.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] These orders of magnitude do not take into consideration the velocity of the Brownian particle, U, which actively depends on the collisions that tend to accelerate and decelerate it.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The larger U is, the greater will be the resistive drag of collisions that will retard it, so that the velocity of a Brownian particle can never increase without limit.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] If such an unbounded process could occur, it would be tantamount to a perpetual motion machine of the second kind.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Since the equipartition of energy applies to this system in thermal equilibrium, the kinetic energy of the Brownian particle, ${\textstyle MU^{2}/2}$ , will be equal, on the average, to the kinetic energy of the surrounding fluid particle, ${\textstyle mu^{2}/2}$ .
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] In 1906, Smoluchowski published a one-dimensional model to describe a particle undergoing Brownian motion.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The model assumes collisions with ${\textstyle M\gg m}$ where M is the test particle's mass and m the mass of one of the individual particles composing the fluid.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] If ${\textstyle N_{\text{R}}}$ is the number of collisions from the right and ${\textstyle N_{\text{L}}}$ the number of collisions from the left then after N collisions the particle's velocity will have changed by ${\textstyle \Delta V(2N_{\text{R}}-N)}$ .
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The multiplicity is then simply given by: ${\binom {N}{N_{\text{R}}}}={\frac {N!}{N_{\text{R}}!(N-N_{\text{R}})!}}$ and the total number of possible states is given by ${\textstyle 2^{N}}$ .
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] As a result of its simplicity, Smoluchowski's 1D model can only qualitatively describe Brownian motion.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] For a realistic particle undergoing Brownian motion in a fluid, many of the assumptions do not apply.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] For example, the assumption that on average there are an equal number of collisions from the right as from the left falls apart once the particle is in motion, as it will sweep into particles in its path and create a velocity-dependent drag force.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Furthermore, there would be a continuous statistical distribution of different possible ${\textstyle \Delta V}$ s governed by the Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution of fluid molecule velocities, rather than a single discrete value in a physical liquid or gas.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The diffusion equation yields an approximation of the time evolution of the probability density function associated with the position of the particle going under a Brownian movement under the physical definition.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The approximation becomes valid on timescales much larger than the timescale of individual atomic collisions, since it does not include a term to describe the acceleration of particles during collision.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The time evolution of the position of the Brownian particle over all time scales described using the Langevin equation, an equation that involves a random force field representing the effect of the thermal fluctuations of the solvent on the particle.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] At longer times scales, where acceleration is negligible, individual particle dynamics can be approximated using Brownian dynamics in place of Langevin dynamics.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] In stellar dynamics, a massive body (star, black hole, etc.) can experience Brownian motion as it responds to gravitational forces from surrounding stars.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The rms velocity V of the massive object, of mass M, is related to the rms velocity $v_{\star }$ of the background stars by $MV^{2}\approx mv_{\star }^{2}$ where $m\ll M$ is the mass of the background stars.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The gravitational force from the massive object causes nearby stars to move faster than they otherwise would, increasing both $v_{\star }$ and V.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The Brownian velocity of Sgr A*, the supermassive black hole at the center of the Milky Way galaxy, is predicted from this formula to be less than 1 km s−1.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] In mathematics, Brownian motion is described by the **Wiener process**, a continuous-time stochastic process named in honor of Norbert Wiener.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] It is one of the best known Lévy processes (càdlàg stochastic processes with stationary independent increments) and occurs frequently in pure and applied mathematics, economics and physics.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] ${\mathcal {N}}(\mu ,\sigma ^{2})$ denotes the normal distribution with expected value μ and variance *σ*2.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] In addition, for some filtration ${\mathcal {F}}_{t}$ , $W_{t}$ is ${\mathcal {F}}_{t}$ measurable for all $t\geq 0$ .
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] An alternative characterisation of the Wiener process is the so-called *Lévy characterisation* that says that the Wiener process is an almost surely continuous martingale with *W*0 = 0 and quadratic variation $[W_{t},W_{t}]=t$ .
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] A third characterisation is that the Wiener process has a spectral representation as a sine series whose coefficients are independent ${\mathcal {N}}(0,1)$ random variables.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] This representation can be obtained using the Kosambi–Karhunen–Loève theorem.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The Wiener process can be constructed as the scaling limit of a random walk, or other discrete-time stochastic processes with stationary independent increments.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Like the random walk, the Wiener process is recurrent in one or two dimensions (meaning that it returns almost surely to any fixed neighborhood of the origin infinitely often) whereas it is not recurrent in dimensions three and higher.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Unlike the random walk, it is scale invariant.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The Brownian motion can be modeled by a random walk.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] In the general case, Brownian motion is a Markov process and described by stochastic integral equations.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The French mathematician Paul Lévy proved the following theorem, which gives a necessary and sufficient condition for a continuous **R***n*-valued stochastic process *X* to actually be n-dimensional Brownian motion.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Hence, Lévy's condition can actually be used as an alternative definition of Brownian motion.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Let *X* = (*X*1, ..., *X**n*) be a continuous stochastic process on a probability space (Ω, Σ, **P**) taking values in **R***n*.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] 2. for all 1 ≤ *i*, *j* ≤ *n*, *X**i*(*t*) *X**j*(*t*) − *δ**ij* *t* is a martingale with respect to **P** (and its own natural filtration), where *δ**ij* denotes the Kronecker delta.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The spectral content of a stochastic process $X_{t}$ can be found from the power spectral density, formally defined as $S(\omega )=\lim _{T\to \infty }{\frac {1}{T}}\mathbb {E} \left\{\left|\int _{0}^{T}e^{i\omega t}X_{t}dt\right|^{2}\right\},$ where $\mathbb {E}$ stands for the expected value.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The power spectral density of Brownian motion is found to be $S_{BM}(\omega )={\frac {4D}{\omega ^{2}}}.$ where D is the diffusion coefficient of *Xt*.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] For sufficiently long realization times, the expected value of the power spectrum of a single trajectory converges to the formally defined power spectral density $S(\omega )$ , but its coefficient of variation $\gamma =\sigma /\mu$ tends to ${\sqrt {5}}/2$ .
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] This implies the distribution of $S^{(1)}(\omega ,T)$ is broad even in the infinite time limit.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Brownian motion is usually considered to take place in Euclidean space.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] It is natural to consider how such motion generalizes to more complex shapes, such as surfaces or higher dimensional manifolds.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The formalization requires the space to possess some form of a derivative, as well as a metric, so that a Laplacian can be defined.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Both of these are available on Riemannian manifolds.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Riemannian manifolds have the property that geodesics can be described in polar coordinates; that is, displacements are always in a radial direction, at some given angle.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Uniform random motion is then described by Gaussians along the radial direction, independent of the angle, the same as in Euclidean space.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The infinitesimal generator (and hence characteristic operator) of Brownian motion on Euclidean **R***n* is ⁠1/2⁠Δ, where Δ denotes the Laplace operator.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] Brownian motion on an m-dimensional Riemannian manifold (*M*, *g*) can be defined as diffusion on M with the characteristic operator given by ⁠1/2⁠ΔLB, half the Laplace–Beltrami operator ΔLB.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] One of the topics of study is a characterization of the Poincaré recurrence time for such systems.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] The narrow escape problem is that of calculating the mean escape time.
[src:brownian-motion/brownian-motion] This time diverges as the window shrinks, thus rendering the calculation a singular perturbation problem.
[src:brownian-motion/diffusion-process] In probability theory and statistics, **diffusion processes** are a class of continuous-time Markov process with almost surely continuous sample paths.
[src:brownian-motion/diffusion-process] Diffusion processes are stochastic in nature and hence are used to model many real-life stochastic systems.
[src:brownian-motion/diffusion-process] Brownian motion, reflected Brownian motion and Ornstein–Uhlenbeck processes are examples of diffusion processes.
[src:brownian-motion/diffusion-process] It is used heavily in statistical physics, statistical analysis, information theory, data science, neural networks, finance and marketing.
[src:brownian-motion/diffusion-process] A sample path of a diffusion process models the trajectory of a particle embedded in a flowing fluid and subjected to random displacements due to collisions with other particles, which is called Brownian motion.
[src:brownian-motion/diffusion-process] The position of the particle is then random; its probability density function as a function of space and time is governed by a convection–diffusion equation.
[src:brownian-motion/diffusion-process] A *diffusion process* is a Markov process with continuous sample paths for which the Kolmogorov forward equation is the Fokker–Planck equation.
[src:brownian-motion/diffusion-process] A diffusion process is defined by the following properties.
[src:brownian-motion/diffusion-process] Let $a^{ij}(x,t)$ be uniformly continuous coefficients and $b^{i}(x,t)$ be bounded, Borel measurable drift terms.
[src:brownian-motion/diffusion-process] To see this, let $X_{t}$ solve the SDE starting at $X_{\tau }=\xi$ .
[src:brownian-motion/diffusion-process] The law of $X_{t}$ defines $\mathbb {P} _{a;b}^{\xi ,\tau }$ on $\Omega =C([0,\infty ),\mathbb {R} ^{d})$ with the correct initial condition and local martingale property.
[src:brownian-motion/diffusion-process] Uniqueness follows from the Lipschitz continuity of $\sigma \!,\!b$ .
[src:brownian-motion/diffusion-process] In fact, $L_{a;b}+{\tfrac {\partial }{\partial s}}$ coincides with the infinitesimal generator ${\mathcal {A}}$ of this process.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] The equation can be generalized to other observables as well.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] The Fokker–Planck equation has multiple applications in information theory, graph theory, data science, finance, economics, etc.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] It is named after Adriaan Fokker and Max Planck, who described it in 1914 and 1917.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] It is also known as the **Kolmogorov forward equation**, after Andrey Kolmogorov, who independently discovered it in 1931.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] When applied to particle position distributions, it is better known as the **Smoluchowski equation** (after Marian Smoluchowski), and in this context it is equivalent to the convection–diffusion equation.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] When applied to particle position and momentum distributions, it is known as the Klein–Kramers equation.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] The case with zero diffusion is the continuity equation.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] The Fokker–Planck equation is obtained from the master equation through Kramers–Moyal expansion.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] The first consistent microscopic derivation of the Fokker–Planck equation in the single scheme of classical and quantum mechanics was performed by Nikolay Bogoliubov and Nikolay Krylov.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] In the following, use $\sigma ={\sqrt {2D}}$ .
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] Changing the dummy variable y to x , one gets ${\begin{aligned}\int p(x)\lim _{\Delta t\to 0}{\frac {1}{\Delta t}}\left(\mathbb {P} _{t+\Delta t,t'}(x\mid x')-\mathbb {P} _{t,t'}(x\mid x')\right)\,dx,\end{aligned}}$ which is a time derivative.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] Finally we arrive to $\int [{\mathcal {L}}p(x)]\mathbb {P} _{t,t'}(x\mid x')\,dx=\int p(x)\,{\frac {\partial }{\partial t}}\mathbb {P} _{t,t'}(x\mid x')\,dx.$ From here, the Kolmogorov backward equation can be deduced.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] Remains the issue of defining explicitly ${\mathcal {L}}$ .
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] The part that depends on $dW_{t}$ vanished because of the martingale property.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] The Fokker–Planck equation is used with problems where the initial distribution is known.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] If, instead, a final point is fixed, the Feynman–Kac formula can be used to calculate expectation values such as mean first-passage times, which is a consequence of the Kolmogorov backward equation.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] If the problem is to know the distribution at previous times, starting from a known distribution at later times, a reverse-time Fokker-Planck equation can be constructed.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] This convention is more often used in physical applications.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] Indeed, it is well known that any solution to the Stratonovich SDE is a solution to the Itô SDE.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] where the linear operator ${\mathcal {A}}^{*}$ is the Hermitian adjoint to the infinitesimal generator for the Markov process.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] Here the drift term is zero and the diffusion coefficient is 1/2.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] which is the simplest form of a diffusion equation.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] The Boltzmann distribution $p(x)\propto e^{-U(x)/k_{\text{B}}T}$ is an equilibrium distribution, and assuming U grows sufficiently rapidly (that is, the potential well is deep enough to confine the particle), the Boltzmann distribution is the unique equilibrium.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] Other particles in the medium will randomly kick the particle as they collide with it and this effect can be approximated by a white noise term; $\sigma (dW_{t}/dt)$ .
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] Taking $m=1$ for simplicity and changing the notation as $V_{t}\rightarrow X_{t}$ leads to the familiar form $dX_{t}=-aX_{t}dt+\sigma dW_{t}$ .
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] In plasma physics, the distribution function for a particle species s , $p_{s}(\mathbf {x} ,\mathbf {v} ,t)$ , takes the place of the probability density function.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] where the third term includes the particle acceleration due to the Lorentz force and the Fokker–Planck term at the right-hand side represents the effects of particle collisions.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] The quantities $\langle \Delta v_{i}\rangle$ and $\langle \Delta v_{i}\,\Delta v_{j}\rangle$ are the average change in velocity a particle of type s experiences due to collisions with all other particle species in unit time.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] Expressions for these quantities are given elsewhere.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] If collisions are ignored, the Boltzmann equation reduces to the Vlasov equation.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] Consider an overdamped Brownian particle under external force $F(r)$ : $m{\ddot {r}}=-\gamma {\dot {r}}+F(r)+\sigma \xi (t)$ where the $m{\ddot {r}}$ term is negligible (the meaning of "overdamped").
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] The Fokker–Planck equation for this particle is the Smoluchowski diffusion equation: ${\frac {\partial }{\partial t}}P(r,t\mid r_{0},t_{0})=\nabla \cdot \left[D\left(\nabla -\beta F(r)\right)P(r,t\mid r_{0},t_{0})\right]$ where D is the diffusion constant and $\beta ={\frac {1}{k_{\text{B}}T}}$ .
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] The importance of this equation is it allows for both the inclusion of the effect of temperature on the system of particles and a spatially dependent diffusion constant.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] Starting with the Langevin Equation of a Brownian particle in external field $F(r)$ , where $\gamma$ is the friction term, $\xi$ is a fluctuating force on the particle, and $\sigma$ is the amplitude of the fluctuation.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] At equilibrium the frictional force is much greater than the inertial force, $\left\vert \gamma {\dot {r}}\right\vert \gg \left\vert m{\ddot {r}}\right\vert$ .
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] **Note**, the diffusion coefficient may not necessarily be spatially independent if $\sigma$ or $\gamma$ are spatially dependent.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] Therefore, the flux of particles can be determined by taking the time derivative of the number of particles in a given volume, plugging in the Fokker–Planck equation, and then applying Gauss's Theorem.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] In equilibrium, it is assumed that the flux goes to zero.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] Therefore, Boltzmann statistics can be applied for the probability of a particles location at equilibrium, where $F(r)=-\nabla U(r)$ is a conservative force and the probability of a particle being in a state r is given as $P(r,t\mid r_{0},t_{0})={\frac {e^{-\beta U(r)}}{Z}}$ .
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] This relation is a realization of the fluctuation–dissipation theorem.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] Brownian motion follows the Langevin equation, which can be solved for many different stochastic forcings with results being averaged (canonical ensemble in molecular dynamics).
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] Brownian dynamics in one dimension is simple.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] where the diffusion constant, D , is constant over space and time.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] The boundary conditions are such that the probability vanishes at $x\rightarrow \pm \infty$ with an initial condition of the ensemble of particles starting in the same place, $P(x,t{=}t_{0}|x_{0},t_{0})=\delta (x-x_{0})$ .
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] The simulation on the right was completed using a Brownian dynamics simulation.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] Starting with a Langevin equation for the system, $m{\ddot {x}}=-\gamma {\dot {x}}-c+\sigma \xi (t)$ where $\gamma$ is the friction term, $\xi$ is a fluctuating force on the particle, and $\sigma$ is the amplitude of the fluctuation.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] At equilibrium the frictional force is much greater than the inertial force, $\left|\gamma {\dot {x}}\right|\gg \left|m{\ddot {x}}\right|$ .
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] For the Brownian dynamic simulation the fluctuation force $\xi (t)$ is assumed to be Gaussian with the amplitude being dependent of the temperature of the system ${\textstyle \sigma ={\sqrt {2\gamma k_{\text{B}}T}}}$ .
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] The integration of this equation was done using the Euler–Maruyama method to numerically approximate the path of this Brownian particle.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] Being a partial differential equation, the Fokker–Planck equation can be solved analytically only in special cases.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] A formal analogy of the Fokker–Planck equation with the Schrödinger equation allows the use of advanced operator techniques known from quantum mechanics for its solution in a number of cases.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] Furthermore, in the case of overdamped dynamics when the Fokker–Planck equation contains second partial derivatives with respect to all spatial variables, the equation can be written in the form of a master equation that can easily be solved numerically.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] In many applications, one is only interested in the steady-state probability distribution $p_{0}(x)$ , which can be found from ${\textstyle {\frac {\partial p(x,t)}{\partial t}}=0}$ .
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] The computation of mean first passage times and splitting probabilities can be reduced to the solution of an ordinary differential equation which is intimately related to the Fokker–Planck equation.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] In mathematical finance for volatility smile modeling of options via local volatility, one has the problem of deriving a diffusion coefficient ${\sigma }(\mathbf {X} _{t},t)$ consistent with a probability density obtained from market option quotes.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] The problem is therefore an inversion of the Fokker–Planck equation: Given the density f(x,t) of the option underlying *X* deduced from the option market, one aims at finding the local volatility ${\sigma }(\mathbf {X} _{t},t)$ consistent with *f*.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] This is an inverse problem that has been solved in general by Dupire (1994, 1997) with a non-parametric solution.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] Brigo and Mercurio (2002, 2003) propose a solution in parametric form via a particular local volatility ${\sigma }(\mathbf {X} _{t},t)$ consistent with a solution of the Fokker–Planck equation given by a mixture model.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] More information is available also in Fengler (2008), Gatheral (2008), and Musiela and Rutkowski (2008).
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] Every Fokker–Planck equation is equivalent to a path integral.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] The path integral formulation is an excellent starting point for the application of field theory methods.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] This is used, for instance, in critical dynamics.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] A derivation of the path integral is possible in a similar way as in quantum mechanics.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] The derivation for a Fokker–Planck equation with one variable x is as follows.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] The x -derivatives here only act on the $\delta$ -function, not on $p(x,t)$ .
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] This equation expresses $p(x',t{+}\varepsilon )$ as functional of $p(x,t)$ .
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] The variables ${\tilde {x}}$ conjugate to x are called "response variables".
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] Although formally equivalent, different problems may be solved more easily in the Fokker–Planck equation or the path integral formulation.
[src:brownian-motion/fokker-planck-equation] The equilibrium distribution for instance may be obtained more directly from the Fokker–Planck equation.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] In probability theory, **fractional Brownian motion** (**fBm**), also called a **fractal Brownian motion**, is a generalization of Brownian motion.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] where *H* is a real number in (0, 1), called the Hurst index or Hurst parameter associated with the fractional Brownian motion.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] The Hurst exponent describes the raggedness of the resultant motion, with a higher value leading to a smoother motion.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] It was introduced by Mandelbrot & van Ness (1968).
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] Fractional Brownian motion has stationary increments *X*(*t*) = *BH*(*s*+*t*) − *BH*(*s*) (the value is the same for any *s*).
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] The increment process *X*(*t*) is known as **fractional Gaussian noise**.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] There is also a generalization of fractional Brownian motion: ***n*-th order fractional Brownian motion**, abbreviated as n-fBm. n-fBm is a Gaussian, self-similar, non-stationary process whose increments of order *n* are stationary.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] Like the Brownian motion that it generalizes, fractional Brownian motion is named after 19th century biologist Robert Brown; fractional Gaussian noise is named after mathematician Carl Friedrich Gauss.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] where integration is with respect to the white noise measure *dB*(*s*).
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] This integral turns out to be ill-suited as a definition of fractional Brownian motion because of its over-emphasis of the origin (Mandelbrot & van Ness 1968, p.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] for *t* > 0 (and similarly for *t* < 0).
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] The resulting process has stationary increments.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] The main difference between fractional Brownian motion and regular Brownian motion is that while the increments in Brownian Motion are independent, increments for fractional Brownian motion are not.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] If H > 1/2, then there is positive autocorrelation: if there is an increasing pattern in the previous steps, then it is likely that the current step will be increasing as well.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] If H < 1/2, the autocorrelation is negative.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] This property is due to the fact that the covariance function is homogeneous of order 2H and can be considered as a fractal property.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] FBm can also be defined as the unique mean-zero Gaussian process, null at the origin, with stationary and self-similar increments.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] Sample-paths are almost nowhere differentiable.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] With probability 1, the graph of *BH*(*t*) has both Hausdorff dimension and box dimension of 2−*H*.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] As for regular Brownian motion, one can define stochastic integrals with respect to fractional Brownian motion, usually called "fractional stochastic integrals".
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] In general though, unlike integrals with respect to regular Brownian motion, fractional stochastic integrals are not semimartingales.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] Just as Brownian motion can be viewed as white noise filtered by $\omega ^{-2}$ (i.e. integrated), fractional Brownian motion is white noise filtered by $\omega ^{-H-1/2}$ (corresponding to fractional integration).
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] Practical computer realisations of an *fBm* can be generated, although they are only a finite approximation.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] The sample paths chosen can be thought of as showing discrete sampled points on an *fBm* process.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] Three realizations are shown below, each with 1000 points of an *fBm* with Hurst parameter 0.75.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] Realizations of three different types of *fBm* are shown below, each showing 1000 points, the first with Hurst parameter 0.15, the second with Hurst parameter 0.55, and the third with Hurst parameter 0.95.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] The higher the Hurst parameter is, the smoother the curve will be.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] One can simulate sample-paths of an *fBm* using methods for generating stationary Gaussian processes with known covariance function.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] The simplest method relies on the Cholesky decomposition method of the covariance matrix (explained below), which on a grid of size n has complexity of order $O(n^{3})$ .
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] A more complex, but computationally faster method is the circulant embedding method of Dietrich & Newsam (1997).
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] Suppose we want to simulate the values of the *fBM* at times $t_{1},\ldots ,t_{n}$ using the Cholesky decomposition method.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] In order to compute $\,\Sigma$ , we can use for instance the Cholesky decomposition method.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] Note that the result is real-valued because $\lambda _{i}>0$ .
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] Note that since the eigenvectors are linearly independent, the matrix $\,P$ is invertible.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] Where $_{2}F_{1}$ is the Euler hypergeometric integral.
[src:brownian-motion/fractional-brownian-motion] The integral may be efficiently computed by Gaussian quadrature.
[src:brownian-motion/geometric-brownian-motion] A **geometric Brownian motion** (**GBM**), also known as an **exponential Brownian motion**, is a continuous-time stochastic process in which the logarithm of the randomly varying quantity follows a Brownian motion with drift.
[src:brownian-motion/geometric-brownian-motion] It is an important example of stochastic processes satisfying a stochastic differential equation (SDE); in particular, it is used in mathematical finance to model stock prices in the Black–Scholes model.
[src:brownian-motion/geometric-brownian-motion] where $W_{t}$ is a Wiener process or Brownian motion, and $\mu$ ('the percentage drift') and $\sigma$ ('the percentage volatility') are constants.
[src:brownian-motion/geometric-brownian-motion] The former parameter is used to model deterministic trends, while the latter parameter models unpredictable events occurring during the motion.
[src:brownian-motion/geometric-brownian-motion] The derivation requires the use of Itô calculus.
[src:brownian-motion/geometric-brownian-motion] where $dS_{t}\,dS_{t}$ is the quadratic variation of the SDE.
[src:brownian-motion/geometric-brownian-motion] Taking the exponential and multiplying both sides by $S_{0}$ gives the solution claimed above.
[src:brownian-motion/geometric-brownian-motion] where m and $v>0$ are real constants and for an initial condition $X_{0}$ , is called an Arithmetic Brownian Motion (ABM).
[src:brownian-motion/geometric-brownian-motion] This was the model postulated by Louis Bachelier in 1900 for stock prices, in the first published attempt to model Brownian motion, known today as Bachelier model.
[src:brownian-motion/geometric-brownian-motion] As was shown above, the ABM SDE can be obtained through the logarithm of a GBM via Itô's formula.
[src:brownian-motion/geometric-brownian-motion] Similarly, a GBM can be obtained by exponentiation of an ABM through Itô's formula.
[src:brownian-motion/geometric-brownian-motion] When deriving further properties of GBM, use can be made of the SDE of which GBM is the solution, or the explicit solution given above can be used.
[src:brownian-motion/geometric-brownian-motion] For example, consider the stochastic process log(*S**t*).
[src:brownian-motion/geometric-brownian-motion] This is an interesting process, because in the Black–Scholes model it is related to the log return of the stock price.
[src:brownian-motion/geometric-brownian-motion] Taking the expectation yields the same result as above: $\operatorname {E} \log(S_{t})=\log(S_{0})+(\mu -\sigma ^{2}/2)t$ .
[src:brownian-motion/geometric-brownian-motion] GBM can be extended to the case where there are multiple correlated price paths.
[src:brownian-motion/geometric-brownian-motion] Geometric Brownian motion is used to model stock prices in the Black–Scholes model and is the most widely used model of stock price behavior.
[src:brownian-motion/geometric-brownian-motion] Apart from modeling stock prices, Geometric Brownian motion has also found applications in the monitoring of trading strategies.
[src:brownian-motion/geometric-brownian-motion] In an attempt to make GBM more realistic as a model for stock prices, also in relation to the volatility smile problem, one can drop the assumption that the volatility ( $\sigma$ ) is constant.
[src:brownian-motion/geometric-brownian-motion] If we assume that the volatility is a deterministic function of the stock price and time, this is called a local volatility model.
[src:brownian-motion/geometric-brownian-motion] A straightforward extension of the Black Scholes GBM is a local volatility SDE whose distribution is a mixture of distributions of GBM, the lognormal mixture dynamics, resulting in a convex combination of Black Scholes prices for options.
[src:brownian-motion/geometric-brownian-motion] If instead we assume that the volatility has a randomness of its own—often described by a different equation driven by a different Brownian Motion—the model is called a stochastic volatility model, see for example the Heston model.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] In mathematics, the **Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process** is a stochastic process with applications in financial mathematics and the physical sciences.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] Its original application in physics was as a model for the velocity of a massive Brownian particle under the influence of friction.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] It is named after Leonard Ornstein and George Eugene Uhlenbeck.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] The Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process is a stationary Gauss–Markov process, which means that it is a Gaussian process, a Markov process, and is temporally homogeneous.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] In fact, it is the only nontrivial process that satisfies these three conditions, up to allowing linear transformations of the space and time variables.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] Over time, the process tends to drift towards its mean function: such a process is called ***mean-reverting***.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] The Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process can also be considered as the continuous-time analogue of the discrete-time AR(1) process.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] where $\theta >0$ and $\sigma >0$ are parameters and $W_{t}$ denotes the Wiener process.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] where $\mu$ is a constant called the (long-term) mean.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] where $\eta (t)$ , also known as white noise, stands in for the supposed derivative $dW_{t}/dt$ of the Wiener process.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] However, $dW_{t}/dt$ does not exist because the Wiener process is nowhere differentiable, and so the Langevin equation only makes sense if interpreted in distributional sense.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] In physics and engineering disciplines, it is a common representation for the Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process and similar stochastic differential equations by tacitly assuming that the noise term is a derivative of a differentiable (e.g.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] Fourier) interpolation of the Wiener process.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] The Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process can also be described in terms of a probability density function, $P(x,t)$ , which specifies the probability of finding the process in the state x at time t .
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] This is a linear parabolic partial differential equation which can be solved by a variety of techniques.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] This gives the probability of the state x occurring at time t given initial state $x_{0}$ at time $t_{0}<t$ .
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] Equivalently, $P(x,t\mid x_{0},t_{0})$ is the solution of the Fokker–Planck equation with initial condition $P(x,t_{0})=\delta (x-x_{0})$ .
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] For the stationary (unconditioned) process, the mean of $x_{t}$ is $\mu$ , and the covariance of $x_{s}$ and $x_{t}$ is ${\frac {\sigma ^{2}}{2\theta }}e^{-\theta |t-s|}$ .
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] The Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process is an example of a Gaussian process that has a bounded variance and admits a stationary probability distribution, in contrast to the Wiener process; the difference between the two is in their "drift" term.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] In other words, the mean acts as an equilibrium level for the process.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] where $W_{t}$ is the standard Wiener process.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] This is roughly Theorem 1.2 in Doob 1942.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] Using this mapping, one can translate known properties of $W_{t}$ into corresponding statements for $x_{t}$ .
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] The stochastic differential equation for $x_{t}$ can be formally solved by variation of parameters.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] Its solutions are $\phi (y)=He_{n}(y)$ , with $\lambda =-n\theta$ , which implies that the mean first passage time for a particle to hit a point on the boundary is on the order of $\theta ^{-1}$ .
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] By using discretely sampled data at time intervals of width t , the maximum likelihood estimators for the parameters of the Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process are asymptotically normal to their true values.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] $x(t+dt)=x(t)-\Theta \,dt\,x(t)+\Sigma {\sqrt {2\,dt\,\Theta }}\nu _{i}$ where $\nu _{i}$ is a normally distributed random number with zero mean and unit variance, sampled independently at every time-step $dt$ .
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] The Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process can be interpreted as a scaling limit of a discrete process, in the same way that Brownian motion is a scaling limit of random walks.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] Consider an urn containing n black and white balls.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] At each step a ball is chosen at random and replaced by a ball of the opposite colour.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] Let $X_{k}$ be the number of black balls in the urn after k steps.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] Then ${\frac {X_{[nt]}-n/2}{\sqrt {n}}}$ converges in law to an Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process as n tends to infinity.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] Heuristically one may obtain this as follows.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] Let $X_{t}^{(n)}:={\frac {X_{[nt]}-n/2}{\sqrt {n}}}$ , and we will obtain the stochastic differential equation at the $n\to \infty$ limit.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] The Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process is a prototype of a noisy relaxation process.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] A canonical example is a Hookean spring (harmonic oscillator) with spring constant k whose dynamics is overdamped with friction coefficient $\gamma$ .
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] where $\sigma ^{2}$ is derived from the Stokes–Einstein equation $D=k_{B}T/\gamma$ for the effective diffusion constant.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] This model has been used to characterize the motion of a Brownian particle in an optical trap.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] At equilibrium, the spring stores an average energy $\langle E\rangle =k\langle (x-x_{0})^{2}\rangle /2=k_{B}T/2$ in accordance with the equipartition theorem.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] The Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process is used in the Vasicek model of the interest rate.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] The Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process is one of several approaches used to model (with modifications) interest rates, currency exchange rates, and commodity prices stochastically.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] The parameter $\mu$ represents the equilibrium or mean value supported by fundamentals; $\sigma$ the degree of volatility around it caused by shocks, and $\theta$ the rate by which these shocks dissipate and the variable reverts towards the mean.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] One application of the process is a trading strategy known as pairs trade.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] A further implementation of the Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process is derived by Marcello Minenna in order to model the stock return under a lognormal distribution dynamics.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] This modeling aims at the determination of confidence interval to predict market abuse phenomena.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] The Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process has been proposed as an improvement over a Brownian motion model for modeling the change in organismal phenotypes over time.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] A Brownian motion model implies that the phenotype can move without limit, whereas for most phenotypes natural selection imposes a cost for moving too far in either direction.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] A meta-analysis of 250 fossil phenotype time-series showed that an Ornstein–Uhlenbeck model was the best fit for 115 (46%) of the examined time series, supporting stasis as a common evolutionary pattern.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] This said, there are certain challenges to its use: model selection mechanisms are often biased towards preferring an OU process without sufficient support, and misinterpretation is easy to the unsuspecting data scientist.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] Here, the differential of the Wiener process $W_{t}$ has been replaced with the differential of a Lévy process $L_{t}$ .
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] In addition, in finance, stochastic processes are used where the volatility increases for larger values of X .
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] In particular, the CKLS process (Chan–Karolyi–Longstaff–Sanders) with the volatility term replaced by $\sigma \,x^{\gamma }\,dW_{t}$ can be solved in closed form for $\gamma =1$ , as well as for $\gamma =0$ , which corresponds to the conventional OU process.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] Another special case is $\gamma =1/2$ , which corresponds to the Cox–Ingersoll–Ross model (CIR-model).
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] where $\mathbf {W} _{t}$ is an *N*-dimensional Wiener process, and ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ and ${\boldsymbol {\sigma }}$ are constant *N*×*N* matrices.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] These expressions make use of the matrix exponential.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] where the matrix ${\boldsymbol {D}}$ with components $D_{ij}$ is defined by ${\boldsymbol {D}}={\boldsymbol {\sigma }}{\boldsymbol {\sigma }}^{T}/2$ .
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] Like for the one-dimensional case, the process is a linear transformation of Gaussian random variables, and therefore itself must be Gaussian.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] Because of this, the transition probability $P(\mathbf {x} ,t\mid \mathbf {x} ',t')$ is a Gaussian which can be written down explicitly.
[src:brownian-motion/ornstein-uhlenbeck-process] where the matrix ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}$ is determined from the Lyapunov equation ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}{\boldsymbol {\omega }}+{\boldsymbol {\omega }}{\boldsymbol {\beta }}^{T}=2{\boldsymbol {D}}$ .
